\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Grey, grey, grey,\u8221\'94 Colm Triton muttered, shaking his head in disgust. He was still several leagues out from his legion\u8217\'92s bivouac, but already the scene was damnable. For as far as the fog revealed, the trees had been hewn for lumber, and their ugly stumps pocked the rolling foothills like warts on an ogre\u8217\'92s ass - and it was all just as grey, just as muddy, just as riddled with tufts of fungus. Absent sun and absent shadows, the land was absent life.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Cursed,\u8221\'94 was the word that sprung to Colm\u8217\'92s mind. It was as if all the trees and bush and bramble had fled the place. Even the stoutest rocks seemed to want to burrow into the ground. Yet, men made their way into the valley from every corner of the Empire to swell the ranks of the Mud Legion.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Whether they were all brave or stupid, Colm was\~ unsure, but he was one of them all the same.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~He eyed his comrades warily, noting how each face was more sullen and weary than the last. Just skin and bones, save a few.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We\u8217\'92re fools, at the very least,\u8221\'94 Colm reasoned. Only a column of fools would march towards the thing from which mutilated soldiers limped away. No clearer display of their prospects in battle could be arranged than those that littered the highway: A weary captain slumped in his saddle, arm slung tight to his chest. A footman whose whole head was swaddled in bloodstained rags. Another with no wounds to rival his comrades, but his face wore their trauma all the same.\~\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In this last day alone Colm\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s troop had passed twelve of these decimated companies, and yet they kept marching. So, brave or stupid, they were fools at the very least, brave fools as they may be.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But there were far more people heading towards the camp than away, and it pleased Colm to see that most of these weren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t soldiers. That meant the camp, and the wall that it worked to maintain, had reached some measure of stability.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A distant, roaring horn.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Its echo muted the rumbling of wagon wheels and the squelching of mud underfoot.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 An Orc horn, sounding like the scream of an Epegrine Eel out of water.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Colm troop take it in like noobs..\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 One of the wounded veterans leaving the front caught Colm\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eye. He seemed to be laughing at them. A bloody stump of a left arm and yet he laughed.\line \u8220\'93Hear that Comrades?\u8221\'94 the laughing wretch asked. \u8220\'93The horn blows for you! Go and earn your wages!\u8221\'94 At that he reached into the wagon next to him and pulled out a bag of coin and shook it. \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92ll only cost an arm or a leg!\u8221\'94\~ The other weary sods around him laughed, but not even this bit of humor pausing their rueful exodus.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Fool\u8217\'92s gone mad,\u8221\'94 said the former beggar boy, Trim, who marched to Colm\u8217\'92s left.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No, I don\u8217\'92t think so.\u8221\'94 said Colm. \u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s you or me in three months.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You or me?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Did you count how many men were left in that poor sod\u8217\'92s column? Less than half I\u8217\'92d wager.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, we could both be part of the less-than-half that lives,\u8221\'94 said Trim.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The fallen priest to Colm\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s right chuckled at Trim\u8217\'92s innocent resolve - but it didn\u8217\'92t go too far as his neck was wrung so tight by the chain of excommunication that he struggled even to breathe. In fact, that chuckle was the first peep Colm had heard from the scrawny young heretic since their journey began twelve weeks ago.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Colm appreciated how, as a group, they formed a neat tableau of the waste product that oozed out from the Empire\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s machinery. Colm himself typified the numberless poor that wandered the countryside, somehow lucky enough to be born a freeman, but had done nothing with it and so was forced, at thirty, into soldiery. Trim was refuse from the Capital. Here too was an excommunicated priest. There was even a woman, marching right ahead of Colm. She was at least forty, with skin as leathery as the Sergeant who had assembled them. Still, Colm had made his passes at her. In their months of marching, all he had gotten in return was a nasty array of scowles.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 amped in that desolate place for five months, more than long enough for their twenty thousand white canvas tents to become so thickly matted grey with grime that Colm Triton mistook them for massive rocks strewn about by a landslide.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What am i doing...\u8221\'94 he muttered as he crested the last foothill. From there he could see the Mud Legion\u8217\'92s camp in its entirety; a city unto itself.\~ People everywhere, headed to and fro. Soldiers, families, a whole network of eager merchant stalls. Thousands upon thousands of cattle grazing in the shadow of the northern range. Buildings too, perhaps a thousand of them, worked up against each other, stilted and shanty. It had the makings of a metropolis. Present, even, was the stupefying haze of smoke and stink and clamour.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Colm let it wash over him in a nostalgic embrace.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A proper writhing mass of humanity. Perhaps a hundred thousand.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He inhaled deeply and let the seasoned vapors fill his lungs before letting loose a contented sigh. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Glory to the Empire,\u8221\'94 he whispered.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He could sense opportunity nestled in every nook and cranny of that sprawling micro-nation. All thoughts of woe and dread were driven from his mind in an instant. As if sharing Colm\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s rapture, Trim said aside, \u8220\'93The orcs don\u8217\'92t stand a chance. Not a chance!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes boy! Not a chance!\u8221\'94 shouted the Sergeant in reply as he hopped up on the back of one of their carts so that the troop could eye him neatly.\~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Men!\u8221\'94 he shouted, drawing the rest of the troop to attention. The sergeant was a man\u8217\'92s man and his voice bellowed with vigor. Went by the name of Burgh. \u8220\'93We\u8217\'92re nearly to the front. Once we're through the checkpoint, I\u8217\'92ll drop you off with the rest of the muster while I go fetch our orders. I\u8217\'92ll also see to getting you a key for that thing on your neck,\u8221\'94 he said, motioning to the ex-priest next to Colm. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ll be back with ya\u8217\'92ll by nightfall, so get a fire going. Also, some good news,\u8221\'94 he held up a white slip and flagged it back and forth. \u8220\'93A barrel of beer on arrival, courtesy of the General Elect.\u8221\'94 At that a few cheers went up, and Burgh passed the slip off to his corporal. \u8220\'93Jan here is in charge of it. Don\u8217\'92t give him any beef. Save it for the enemy. And don\u8217\'92t,\u8221\'94 he paused for effect, staring down a few of the more troublesome men, skipping over Colm, \u8220\'93I repeat - do not -\~ get mixed up in anything unsavory. If my ass gets chewed out, your ass gets torn up. So. Orders tonight. Ration the booze till I get back - might have marching sticks on the morrow.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 At that there was a collective groan, but Burgh just laughed as he hopped off the wagon.}
